Sorry, my original thought on approach is not as short as it really will be.  

I think the path we would want to take, detect an easing function with airty during a $.Animaiton.prefilter(), warn about the specific easing function (once only), and then override `jQuery.Tween.prototype.run`, with the current code:

```js
	jQuery.Tween.prototype.run = function( percent ) {
		var eased,
			hooks = Tween.propHooks[ this.prop ];

		if ( this.options.duration ) {
			this.pos = eased = jQuery.easing[ this.easing ](
				percent, this.options.duration * percent, 0, 1, this.options.duration
			);
		} else {
			this.pos = eased = percent;
		}
		this.now = ( this.end - this.start ) * eased + this.start;

		if ( this.options.step ) {
			this.options.step.call( this.elem, this.now, this );
		}

		if ( hooks && hooks.set ) {
			hooks.set( this );
		} else {
			Tween.propHooks._default.set( this );
		}
		return this;
	};
```

Alternatively, we could refactor the version of run that will be shipped in the next version to make the "easing" call abstracted into Tween.prototype.ease( percent ) which we could then back-compat a lot easier (one or two line change vs whole function) -- something like
```js

Tween.prototype.ease = function( percent ) {
  if (this.options.duration) {
    return jQuery.easing[ this.easing ]( percent );
  }
  return percent;
}
```

and then we can make that weird if with the easings just this.pos = this.ease( percent );

