@pmneila I assume you mean scikit-image. =D

My [self-appointed title is Guardian of the Dimensions](https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/pull/1038#issuecomment-47189573), because in fact I *always* try to push PRs to support 3D and even nD where possible. (@emmanuelle is Vice-Guardian. =P) There's many, many functions supporting nD in scikit-image (see the [release notes](http://scikit-image.org/docs/dev/release_notes_and_installation.html), for example, or grep for "3D" in the repo). The main reason that there are not more examples in the docs is that 3D viz in Python is sadly lacking, so it's hard to demonstrate these tools. If you have suggestions about this, we would welcome them!

Finally, yes, the convention is `multichannel={True,False}`. If `True`, the final dimension is considered channels. Again, feel free to grep for this for some examples. =)

@mzsanford ah I see. The problem here is that our circleci tests do not pull anything into `./.git/refs/heads/pull`, so the test for that will fail. I was confused about why this was not an issue before, and digging into it, it seems like our assertion `assertIsNotNone` was getting passed `'None'`, which actually passes. So it was broken but not causing the test to fail. Your fix here exposed this, which is great.

@phumpal had a great suggestion to use `$CIRCLE_SHA1`. For now I think we should check this, and if it's set, skip the assertion `self.assertIsNotNone(rev_file)`. We'll need to find a way to solve this more long-term on circleci, I imagine there's some configuration to pull in these git ref files.

