@troydai or not :)
https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/blob/56bfba8c830ae2d4a5438d0fca9d7c0a0bf0150a/src/azure-cli-core/azure/cli/core/commands/__init__.py#L539

I return an iterator, and you cast it as a list :)

Show if you want information on a specific thing. List if you want to know all the things in either the subscription or resource group (for those services that support both). List is handy because it requires fewer parameters. You could filter the list down and replicate the output of show, but that would require more effort than simply doing the show.

You could have a structure like:
```Python
def command(resource_group=None, name=None):
  if resource_group and name:
     return sdk.get(resource_group, name)
  elif resource_group:
     return sdk.list(resource_group)
  else:
     return list-all()
```

The issues with this are (a) the get returns an object, not a list and (b) there's no guarantee that the get returns the same structure as the list.  If the get returns Foo, it is generally the case that the list commands return [Foo]. However, this isn't guaranteed and services could return something like [FooSummary].

Get will always return as much or more than list, while list will return as much or less than get.

@karungithub The paging mechanism of ARM is described here:
https://github.com/Azure/azure-resource-manager-rpc/blob/master/v1.0/resource-api-reference.md#get-resource

If you don't have "nextLink" in the documentation or in what you get from Azure. or the "top" parameter, this probably means that the service does not support paging for this operation.

